<author><name><![CDATA[kevtris]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-06-28T09:25:31-07:00</updated>
<published>2011-06-28T09:25:31-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7910&amp;p=80701#p80701</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7910&amp;p=80701#p80701"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Wireless Controllers]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7910&amp;p=80701#p80701"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">infiniteneslives wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />I do this kind of stuff all the time: <br /><a href="http://www.InfiniteNesLives.com" class="postlink">http://www.InfiniteNesLives.com</a><br /> and am actually working on a prototype for those exact controllers right now.  I need to work out a bug though because his code doesn't filter out the one packet that gets lost from time to time if you're more than 12in from the console<br /><br />I right now I'm just making them compatible with the Wii and USB.  I'd like to make them for the NES and SNES as well in the future.<br /></div><br /><br />If anyone is going to try to make this for the NES, I highly suggest using 4021 shift registers for the NES (or even SNES) side.  Output the button presses on the microcontroller's IO pins, then feed them into the 4021('s) like on a "real" controller. <br /><br />I am dubious about most micros being fast enough to update their outputs to feed the NES... though it MIGHT be possible if you use an interrupt to update the output port when the NES reads a controller bit.  I'd be worried if the game reads 4016 several times in rapid succession if they are only polling one bit to check the start button or similar.  i.e.:<br /><br />ldx #01h<br />stx 4016<br />dex<br />stx 4016<br />lda 4016<br />lda 4016<br />lda 4016<br />lda 4016<br />ror a<br />bcs ...<br /><br />In this case, the micro has to get data ready in 4 6502 clocks, which is around 2.2uS.  This in and of itself isn't too hard, unless it's also trying to receive data and process packets too from the wireless interface.<br /><br />The 4021's at least are super cheap.  You need one for NES, and two for SNES.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=230">kevtris</a> — Tue Jun 28, 2011 9:25 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
