Yeah I'm not really trying to compete with adapters, and I don't claim to be cheap.  I've admitted before if you're looking to save money go with an adapter or do it yourself and I've recommended raphenet's site to a lot of people looking to make their own.  <br /><br />You have to realize how much time goes into making everything I do especially cleaning masses of controllers.   I started making some basic stuff awhile ago only making a few dollars each while my prices compared to adapters to see how they would sell, and I quickly became overloaded.  My only choice was to charge what would make it worth my time or quit.  <br /><br />I probably won't do finished controllers once I'm done with school, but it's a good flexible income for me right now.  <br /><br />My goal in posting up the fact I could make them and give $150-$200 price tag was not to advertise.  I was unclear what he was looking to pay $50 for and more so explaining what hardware like that would have to go for as finished deal.  Really anyone with the skills is much better off making something themselves, not to mention the personal reward that comes with DIY.   <br /><br />It would be nice if some big manufacturer made something like this so you could get everything for $50 like you're saying.  But honestly I doubt there is the enough market for it, and that's why no one's making them...<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4832">infiniteneslives</a> — Sun Jun 26, 2011 8:13 pm</p><hr />
